For years and years every part of industry seems to be specialising. Making things LIGHTER or STRONGER or FASTER Etc. But ALL in their own field!
REAL progress comes when folks think outside-the-box. Like Elon Musk who thinks of a car as being a computer on wheels.
During the war (WW2), industries COLLABORATED with each other to solve problems, and arrived at some great inventions in a fraction of the time it would normally take.
In the UK the likes of JCB, DYSON and Formula One racing are working together, just as TESLA is here, with results that could be even better than the normal machines.

I do hope that after this CV 19 event is over, folks REMEMBER how working with other industries can create things that are better than the sum of their parts! And continue to do so!

snippet.textDisplay: I'm sure this is already known by your team but just in case it isn't. As a former BMET for GE MSIT I would like to remind everyone at Tesla to make sure the power supplies are medical grade. At 2:18 it sounds like he is saying the system is powered by the infotainment system which I'm assuming has an automotive grade power supply. There are some serious potential issues if the power supplies are not medical grade. Also HI-Pot test these units before shipping. You don't want someone being hit with a defibrillator to short the power supply and now you have mains power back to the patient. This could be easily overlooked if your engineers don't have experience in medical devices. This product page explains what I'm talking about. https://www.medicaldesignandoutsourcing.com/ensuring-safety-with-medical-power-solutions/

snippet.textDisplay: Many people don't know this, but a ventilator with slight variability in breathing rate is vastly superior in increasing arterial oxygenation and facilitating recovery of respiratory function compared to one with a fixed rhythmic driver. This is an example of complexity science. Breathing variability like heart rate variability is a measure of physiological resilience. The more the ventilator can mimic this variability, the better. Can Tesla incorporate a variable rate parameter in their ventilator?
snippet.textOriginal: Many people don't know this, but a ventilator with slight variability in breathing rate is vastly superior in increasing arterial oxygenation and facilitating recovery of respiratory function compared to one with a fixed rhythmic driver.
